# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alkaloid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] The chemical compound **1,2-dichloroethane**, commonly known as **ethylene dichloride** (**EDC**), is a chlorinated hydrocarbon.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] It is a colourless liquid with a chloroform-like odour.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] The most common use of 1,2-dichloroethane is in the production of vinyl chloride, which is used to make polyvinyl chloride (PVC) pipes, furniture and automobile upholstery, wall coverings, housewares, and automobile parts.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane is also used generally as an intermediate for other organic chemical compounds, and as a solvent.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] It forms azeotropes with many other solvents, including water (at a boiling point of 70.5 °C or 158.9 °F or 343.6 K) and other chlorocarbons.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Although the *Gezelschap* in practice did not do much in-depth scientific research, they and their publications were highly regarded.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Part of that acknowledgement is that 1,2-dichloroethane was called "Dutch oil" in old chemistry.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] This is also the origin of the archaic term "olefiant gas" (oil-making gas) for ethylene, for in this reaction it is ethylene that makes the Dutch oil.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] "Olefiant gas" is the etymological origin of the modern term "olefins", the family of hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the first member.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Nearly 20 million tons of 1,2-dichloroethane are produced annually in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Approximately 95% of the world's production of 1,2-dichloroethane is used in the production of vinyl chloride monomer (VCM) with hydrogen chloride as a byproduct.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] VCM is the precursor to polyvinyl chloride.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] The hydrogen chloride can be re-used in the production of more 1,2-dichloroethane via the oxychlorination route described above.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane has been used as degreaser and paint remover but this use has phased out due to its toxicity.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] As a useful 'building block' reagent, it is used as an intermediate in the production of diverse organic compounds such as ethylenediamine and higher ethyleneamines.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] In the laboratory it is occasionally used as a source of chlorine, with elimination of ethene and chloride.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Via several steps, 1,2-dichloroethane is a precursor to 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Historically, before leaded petrol was phased out, chloroethanes were used as an additive in petrol to prevent lead buildup in engines.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] It is also toxic (especially by inhalation due to its high vapour pressure) and possibly carcinogenic.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Its high solubility and 50-year half-life in anoxic aquifers make it a perennial pollutant and health risk that is very expensive to treat conventionally, requiring a method of bioremediation.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] While the chemical is not used in consumer products manufactured in the U.S., a case was reported in 2009 of molded plastic consumer products (toys and holiday decorations) from China that released 1,2-dichloroethane into homes at levels high enough to produce cancer risk.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Substitutes are recommended and will vary according to application.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Dioxolane and toluene are possible substitutes as solvents.
[src:alkaloid/1-2-dichloroethane] Dichloroethane is unstable in the presence of aluminium and, when moist, with zinc and iron.
[src:alkaloid/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The enzyme involved in making 1-deoxy-d-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) is DXP synthase.
[src:alkaloid/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The mechanism follows a catalysis of decarboxylative condensation of pyruvate and d-glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate to produce DXP.
[src:alkaloid/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] In addition, the molecule is involved in making thiamine (vitamin B1) and pyridoxol (vitamin B6).
[src:alkaloid/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The non-mevalonate pathway intermediate 1-deoxy-d-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) also acts as a precursor in making isoprenoids in many species such as bacteria, plants, and apicomplexan parasites, contributing to biological diversity.
[src:alkaloid/2-quinolone] The isomer 4-quinolone is the parent of a large class of antibiotics called quinolone antibiotics.
[src:alkaloid/2-quinolone] A prominent example is ciprofloxacin, a broad spectrum antibiotic commonly used for treatment of various infections such as urinary tract infections (UTIs), typhoid, meningitis, gonorrhoea, syphilis, and skin infections.
[src:alkaloid/4-quinolone] The chemical synthesis of quinolones often involves ring-closing reactions.
[src:alkaloid/4-quinolone] Such reactions often install a hydroxyl group (an –OH functional group) on the carbon across from the ring nitrogen (i.e., the C-4 positions).
[src:alkaloid/4-quinolone] An example of such a synthesis is the Camps cyclization, which, depending on starting materials and reaction conditions, can give both 2-hydroxyquinolines (B) and 4-hydroxyquinolines (A) as shown.
[src:alkaloid/4-quinolone] The hydroxyquinolines tautomerize to the quinolones.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP can be manufactured and used as a drug and supplement with the INNTooltip International Nonproprietary Name *oxitriptan*.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Brand names include Cincofarm, Levothym, Levotonine, Oxyfan, Telesol, Tript-OH, and Triptum.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] As a drug, it is used in the treatment of depression and for certain other indications.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP is produced from the amino acid tryptophan through the action of the enzyme tryptophan hydroxylase.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Tryptophan hydroxylase is one of the biopterin-dependent aromatic amino acid hydroxylases.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Production of 5-HTP is the rate-limiting step in 5-HT (serotonin) synthesis.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP is normally rapidly converted to 5-HT by amino acid decarboxylase.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP is decarboxylated to serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine or 5-HT) by the enzyme aromatic-L-amino-acid decarboxylase with the help of vitamin B6.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] This reaction occurs both in nervous tissue and in the liver.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP crosses the blood–brain barrier, while 5-HT does not.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Excess 5-HTP, especially when administered with vitamin B6, is thought to be metabolized and excreted.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Though 5-HTP is found in food only in insignificant quantities, it is a chemical involved intermediately in the metabolism of tryptophan, an amino acid found in all unfractionated foods, with lower total amino acid content correlating with increased tryptophan absorption.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP has been used medically and as a supplement under the name *oxitriptan* in the treatment of depression and for certain other indications.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] As of 2025, there are no current FDA approved medications containing 5-HTP.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] It can be potentiated in combination with a peripherally selective aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (AAAD) inhibitor such as carbidopa or benserazide.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] These agents increase the strength and duration of oxitriptan.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] An investigational combination formulation is oxitriptan/carbidopa.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP robustly produces the head-twitch response (HTR) in rodents when administered at relatively high doses.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] It dose-dependently induces the HTR in mice across a dose range of 50 to 250 mg/kg via intraperitoneal administration, with an inverted U-shaped dose–response curve and maximal induction of the HTR at a dose of 200 mg/kg.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Similarly to the case of 5-HTP, intracerebroventricular injection of serotonin, but not peripheral administration of serotonin, produces the HTR.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The HTR is induced by serotonergic psychedelics like lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD) and psilocybin and is a behavioral proxy of psychedelic effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] It is also suppressed by the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor full agonist 8-OH-DPAT, is greatly augmented by the serotonin 5-HT2C receptor antagonist RS-102221, and is reduced by the trace amine-associated receptor 1 (TAAR1) antagonist EPPTB.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] These *N*-methylated tryptamines are well-known for their psychedelic effects, whereas serotonin itself, without biotransformation, does not seem to produce psychedelic effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP has not been found to produce psychedelic effects in humans, which has been attributed to the high doses required to produce such effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The 5-HTP doses that produce the HTR in rodents are orders of magnitude higher than the doses of 5-HTP that have been used safely and therapeutically in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] It remains unknown whether 5-HTP can produce psychedelic effects in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The highest dosage of 5-HTP that is known to have been evaluated in humans is about 3,000 mg per day.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Serotonin syndrome and associated hallucinations have been reported with overdose of serotonin-elevating drugs, but psychedelic-like effects have not been reported.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Serotonin itself is too hydrophilic to enter serotonergic neurons without the SERT, whereas serotonergic psychedelics and serotonin's *N*-methylated metabolites and analogues are lipophilic and readily enter these neurons.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] These findings may also explain why selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and related serotonergic agents do not produce psychedelic effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The properties of 5-HTP in animal drug discrimination tests have been studied.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP generalizes with the serotonin releasing agent fenfluramine and its cue is markedly potentiated by the selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) fluoxetine.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] However, numerous serotonin receptor antagonists, including methysergide, cyproheptadine, metergoline, methiothepin (metitepine), ketanserin, pirenperone, pizotifen, and mianserin, all failed to block the discriminative stimulus properties of 5-HTP.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Conflictingly however, in a subsequent study, pizotifen was able to fully block the discriminative stimulus properties of 5-HTP.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The inability of serotonin 5-HT2A receptor antagonists to block the discriminative stimulus properties of 5-HTP is in notable contrast to their ability to block the 5-HTP-induced HTR.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] 5-HTP only partially substitutes for LSD in drug discrimination tests, whereas LSD and quipazine fully substitute for 5-HTP.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The full substitution of LSD and quipazine for 5-HTP can be blocked by the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor antagonist ketanserin.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] The findings of drug discrimination tests suggest that 5-HTP has a more complex or compound discriminative stimulus compared to other agents like LSD and that its stimulus properties may not be readily explained by either the serotonin 5-HT1 or 5-HT2 receptors alone.
[src:alkaloid/5-hydroxytryptophan] Instead, a combination of actions at these and/or other receptors may be involved in its stimulus effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT differs from most other serotonergic psychedelics in having much greater activity at the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor in addition to the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In relation to this, 5-MeO-DMT has been described as an "atypical" psychedelic and as producing subjective effects notably distinct from those of DMT and other psychedelics, for instance having a relative lack of visual effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Nonetheless, 5-MeO-DMT reliably produces mystical experiences in most people who take it.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Like DMT, 5-MeO-DMT is only active non-orally and has a very rapid onset and short duration.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, 5-MeO-DMT is 4- to 20-fold more potent than DMT in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Adverse effects of 5-MeO-DMT include sickness, vomiting, headache, chest pressure, fatigue, anxiety, fear, terror, confusion, paranoia, crying, loss of awareness and motor control, and reactivations.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The drug acts as a non-selective serotonin receptor agonist, including of the serotonin 5-HT1A and 5-HT2A receptors, among others.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT was first described by 1936, was first isolated from natural sources by 1959, and was first reported to be hallucinogenic by 1970.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The use of 5-MeO-DMT-containing toad venom was first described in 1984.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It is a controlled substance in some countries, for instance the United States, United Kingdom, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The drug is used recreationally and several deaths have been reported in association with its use.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Use of 5-MeO-DMT is rare compared with other psychedelics, with only 0.003% of the United States general population having reported taking it in 2019 (compared to 8.5% for psilocybin).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is being developed for potential use in medicine in the treatment of neuropsychiatric disorders such as depression.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is used as a recreational drug and as an entheogen.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It is not orally active, requiring a parenteral route such as smoking to produce effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Other non-oral routes such as intravenous injection, intramuscular injection, rectal administration, sublingual administration, or intranasal administration have also less commonly been used.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition to non-oral administration, 5-MeO-DMT can be combined with a monoamine oxidase inhibitor (MAOI) such as the reversible inhibitor of monoamine oxidase A (RIMA) harmaline to allow for oral activity and a much longer duration than it would have otherwise.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, combination of 5-MeO-DMT with MAOIs can also result in accidental overdose, including instances of serotonin syndrome and death.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition to pure synthetic 5-MeO-DMT, it is often used by smoking in the form of the venom taken from the Colorado River toad (*Incilius alvarius*, formerly *Bufo alvarius* and also known as the Sonoran Desert toad).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In his book *TiHKAL* (*Tryptamines I Have Known and Loved*), Alexander Shulgin lists 5-MeO-DMT's dose as 6 to 20 mg smoked or 2 to 3 mg by intravenous injection and its duration as 1 to 2 hours.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Other sources state the dose of 5-MeO-DMT to be 2 to 15 mg smoked and its duration as 5 to 20 minutes or 12 minutes typically.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It has been described as having a steep dose–response curve.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is not orally active at doses of up to at least 35 mg and is almost always used via smoking.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, another report, by Jonathan Ott, found 5-MeO-DMT to be orally active at a dose of 30 mg.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The onset of 5-MeO-DMT smoked is 8 seconds to 1 minute, with peak effects occurring after 2 to 3 minutes, although some report an onset or build-up of as long as 10 to 15 minutes.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The main effects when smoked last about 10 minutes, with a total duration of 20 to 60 minutes.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Taken by intravenous injection, the onset of 5-MeO-DMT is within 1 minute and the duration was 10 minutes in one instance.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Intravenous injection of 5-MeO-DMT has not yet been formally studied.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] With harmaline doses of 70 to 150 mg orally, 5-MeO-DMT becomes orally active at doses of 10 to 25 mg, the onset is 15 to 18 minutes, peak effects occur after 1.5 hours, and the duration is at least 3 or 4 hours.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, harmaline at sufficient doses such as 150 mg or more can add its own hallucinogenic effects to the experience.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The effects of 5-MeO-DMT have been reported by Shulgin.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Behavioral effects included falling over while sitting, curling up in a fetal position, squirming and writhing around, making frightening noises, and alarming other people.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Physical side effects included physical weakness, shakiness, tremors, shivers emanating from the head, center, or heart, and slight nausea.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The taste when smoking was described as mild, with none of the plastic taste of dimethyltryptamine (DMT).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In the case of an unspecified large overdose smoked, the person lapsed into a coma-like state, their face turned purple, they stopped breathing and had to be resuscitated multiple times, and they experienced a several-day psychosis necessitating antipsychotics.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT was described by Shulgin as being remarkably potent, more potent than DMT, and as having a slightly faster onset than DMT when smoked.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] More specifically, it is 4- to 20-fold more potent than DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The drug is said to be a very strong and quite intense hallucinogen.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] There is an ability to break through to a similar space as DMT, but it is said to be "more like receiving grace" and to be much more relaxed than DMT and less terrifying.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] One report commented that 5-MeO-DMT was like adding the MDMA (ecstasy) experience to DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT was one of the only psychedelics in *TiHKAL* that resulted in a plus-four experience on the Shulgin Rating Scale.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Another psychedelic tryptamine that produced similar effects to 5-MeO-DMT was 5-MeO-MiPT at sufficiently high doses smoked.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT seems to be like a cross between DMT and 5-MeO-pyr-T in terms of its effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The latter shares many commonalities with 5-MeO-DMT, but has few or no psychedelic effects and has pronounced negative effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Other 5-methoxytryptamines like 5-MeO-DET and 5-MeO-DPT were plagued by dose-limiting side effects that resulted in Shulgin having an unfavorable impression of them, whereas 5-MeO-DiPT and 5-MeO-DALT produced only light psychedelic effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In other published sources besides *TiHKAL*, the subjective effects of 5-MeO-DMT are described as distinct from those of DMT and other psychedelics.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] These experiences have been described as "beyond ordinary human comprehension", with a subjective impression of a void or amnesia of the experience.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In spite of this however, some have described the experiences as orgasmic, ecstatic, and blissful, whereas others have described them as terror or "information overwhelm".
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] As with DMT and other psychedelics, the experiences with 5-MeO-DMT are often described as overwhelming, profound, spiritual, religious, and/or mystical.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The experiences of 5-MeO-DMT have also been related to the experience of ecstatic seizures.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT has been described as the most powerful psychedelic and by Michael Pollan as the "Mount Everest of psychedelics".
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The phenomenology of 5-MeO-DMT given intransally has been formally clinically studied in a phase 1 clinical trial more recently.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It is described as having a rapid onset of 8 to 15 minutes, a short duration of 45 to 60 minutes, distinctive subjective effects from other psychedelics, a relative lack of visual effects, strong emotional and bodily experiences, emotional breakthroughs, and personal insights, among other effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT has various possible adverse effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] There have been cases of death with 5-MeO-DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The estimated lethal dose of 5-MeO-DMT relative to a typical recreational dose in humans is unknown.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The median lethal dose (LD50) in animals varies widely, ranging from 1 to 5 mg/kg i.v. in sheep to 48 mg/kg i.v. in mice.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In one case, combination of 5-MeO-DMT with harmala alkaloids, which act as monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs), as well as with other drugs, resulted in death.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, the exact contribution of 5-MeO-DMT in this case is difficult to determine.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT can be strongly potentiated by combination with monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, it can become orally active with an extended duration in combination with MAOIs.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] These interactions have the potential to result in serious toxicity and death.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is a methoxylated derivative of dimethyltryptamine (DMT).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] While most common psychedelics are believed to primarily elicit psychological effects through agonism of serotonin 5-HT2A receptors, 5-MeO-DMT shows 1,000-fold greater affinity for the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor over the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In line with its affinity for serotonin 5-HT1A receptors, 5-MeO-DMT is extremely potent at suppressing the firing of dorsal raphe nucleus serotonin neurons.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Further, its activity in rats was attenuated with the selective serotonin 5-HT1A receptor antagonist WAY-100635, while selective serotonin 5-HT2A receptor antagonist volinanserin failed to demonstrate any change.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Additional mechanisms of action such as inhibition of monoamine reuptake may also be involved in its effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Similarly to other serotonergic psychedelics, 5-MeO-DMT is a non-selective serotonin receptor agonist, including of the serotonin 5-HT1A, 5-HT2A, 5-HT2B, and 5-HT2C receptors, among others.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It shows pronounced biased agonism at the serotonin 5-HT2C receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The drug is 4- to 10-fold more potent as a hallucinogen than DMT in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In contrast to most serotonergic psychedelics however, it has been said that it is unclear that the hallucinogenic effects of 5-MeO-DMT are principally mediated by activation of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In any case, 5-MeO-DMT does still activate the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor and does still produce psychedelic effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It has been proposed that 5-MeO-DMT be considered an "atypical" psychedelic.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] This relates to the fact that 5-MeO-DMT has 100- to 1,000-fold selectivity for the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor over the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor and that the actions of 5-MeO-DMT appear to be primarily mediated by serotonin 5-HT1A receptor activation.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, there is partial generalization of 5-MeO-DMT to the selective serotonin 5-HT2 receptor agonist (–)-DOM in animals.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, the selective serotonin 5-HT2A receptor antagonist volinanserin subtly reduces (~20%) the 5-MeO-DMT interoceptive cue, suggesting a minor contribution of this receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Selective antagonists of other serotonin receptors, including the serotonin 5-HT1B, 5-HT2B, and 5-HT2C receptors, had no effect on the discriminative stimulus effects of 5-MeO-DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In accordance with the preceding findings, which suggest effects mediated primarily by the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor and to a lesser extent by the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor, 5-MeO-DMT is reported to produce distinct subjective effects compared to DMT and other psychedelics in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Although 5-MeO-DMT shows dramatically higher affinity for the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor than for the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor, the situation appears to be very different in terms of its actual activational potencies at these receptors.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Its EC50Tooltip half-maximal effective concentration values have been found to be 1.80 to 3.87 nM at the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor and 3.92 to 1,060 nM at the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] For comparison, the EC50 values of DMT were found to be 38.3 nM at the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor and >10,000 nM at the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor in one of the same studies.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Hence, 5-MeO-DMT appears to be similarly potent or as much as 200-fold more potent as an agonist of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor than of the serotonin 5-HT1A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, 5-MeO-DMT is 10-fold more potent than DMT as an agonist of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Besides serotonin receptors, 5-MeO-DMT is an agonist of the melatonin MT1 and MT2 receptors.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Unlike DMT, 5-MeO-DMT is not a ligand or agonist of the sigma receptors.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In contrast to certain other tryptamines, 5-MeO-DMT is inactive as a monoamine releasing agent, including of serotonin, norepinephrine, and dopamine.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, it is a weak serotonin reuptake inhibitor, with an IC50Tooltip half-maximal inhibitory concentration value of 2,184 nM.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Conversely, it is inactive as a dopamine and norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (IC50 = >10,000 nM).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Similarly to DMT, but in contrast to most other psychedelics, like LSD and psilocybin, there appears to be very little development of tolerance with 5-MeO-DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In fact, there may even be sensitization to the effects of 5-MeO-DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The lack of tolerance development with 5-MeO-DMT may be due to biased agonism of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] More specifically, 5-MeO-DMT activates the Gq signaling pathway of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor with much less potency in recruiting β-arrestin2.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Activation of β-arrestin2 is linked to receptor downregulation and tachyphylaxis.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is not orally active and must be administered parenterally.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is lipophilic and is thought to easily cross the blood–brain barrier.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Accordingly, 5-MeO-DMT readily accumulates in the brain in animals with levels higher than in blood.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] This is in notable contrast to bufotenin (5-HO-DMT or *N*,*N*-dimethylserotonin) and serotonin (5-HT), which are hydrophilic and have varying degrees of peripheral selectivity.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Bufotenin is an active metabolite of 5-MeO-DMT, formed by *O*-demethylation by cytochrome P450 CYP2D6.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Bufotenin notably has much higher affinity for the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor than 5-MeO-DMT itself.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] However, bufotenin does not seem to be extensively produced from 5-MeO-DMT in the brain.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, peripherally formed bufotenin is less able to exert central effects due to its relative peripheral selectivity in terms of crossing into the brain.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Hence, the involvement of bufotenin in the psychoactive effects of 5-MeO-DMT is uncertain.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The metabolism of 5-MeO-DMT can be dramatically reduced and its levels markedly augmented and prolonged by monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, MAOIs allow 5-MeO-DMT to become orally active in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Combining 5-MeO-DMT with MAOIs has sometimes resulted in serotonin syndrome and death in humans.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The elimination half-life of 5-MeO-DMT has been found to be 15 to 26 minutes intranasally and 28 minutes sublingually.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Data are not available for other routes such as inhalation or intravenous administration.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT appears to have a longer half-life than dimethyltryptamine (DMT), with the two drugs having half-lives of approximately 20 minutes and 5 minutes, respectively.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT, also known as 5-methoxy-*N*,*N*-dimethyltryptamine, is a substituted tryptamine derivative.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It is the 5-methoxylated derivative of *N*,*N*-dimethyltryptamine (DMT), the *N*,*N*-dimethylated derivative of 5-methoxytryptamine (5-MT; mexamine), and the *O*-methylated derivative of bufotenin (5-HO-DMT).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT has a relatively high experimental log P of 3.30.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The chemical synthesis of 5-MeO-DMT has been described.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Some cyclized tryptamine and/or partial lysergamide derivatives of 5-MeO-DMT include *N*-DEAOP-5-MeO-NMT, 6-MeO-RU-28306, 6-methoxyharmalan, ibogaine, and 12-methoxy-LSD, among others.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] A deuterated isotopologue of 5-MeO-DMT is 5-MeO-DMT-d4 (α,α,β,β-tetradeutero-5-MeO-DMT).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Prodrugs of 5-MeO-DMT such as 1-acetyl-5-MeO-DMT and *N*-phosphonooxymethyl-5-MeO-DMT (*N*-POM-5-MeO-DMT) have also been described.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] There are various known plant sources of 5-MeO-DMT.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Fungal sources of 5-MeO-DMT include *Amanita citrina* and *Amanita porphyria*.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT was first synthesized by Toshio Hoshino in 1935.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It was isolated from the flowering plant *Dictyoloma incanescens* in 1959.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The drug was subsequently isolated from numerous other plant, fungal, and animal sources over time.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The behavioral effects of 5-MeO-DMT in animals were first reported by 1961.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In 1965, 5-MeO-DMT was reported to be the main component of the hallucinogenic snuff known variously as parica, epena, or yakee that is prepared and used from the resin of the *Virola theiodora* tree by indigenous people in Northern South America.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] It was isolated from the toad *Incilius alvarius* (formerly *Bufo alvarius* and also known as the Sonoran Desert toad, Colorado River toad, or simply bufo) by Vittorio Erspamer by 1965.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Alexander Shulgin briefly reported that 5-MeO-DMT was hallucinogenic in humans, via parenteral but not oral routes, in 1970, with additional details published later on.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Albert Most, real name Ken Nelson, was the first to describe the use of *Incilius alvarius* toad venom as a psychedelic in his published pamphlet *Bufo Alvarius: the Psychedelic Toad of the Sonoran Desert* in 1984.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Subsequently, Andrew Weil and Wade Davis, in part citing the pamphlet, described the psychoactive effects of the toad in the scientific literature in 1992.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In addition, they described the finding as the first instance of a psychedelic from an animal source to be discovered.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Recreational use of the toads, beyond the pamphlet, was encountered by the late 1980s and became a media sensation.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT became a controlled substance in the United States in 2009.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The Church of the Tree of Life, founded in California in 1971 by John Mann but now defunct, declared the use of 5-MeO-DMT to be a sacrament.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] From approximately 1971 to the late 1980s, 5-MeO-DMT was discreetly available to its members.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Between 1970 and 1990, smoking of 5-MeO-DMT on parsley was probably one of the two most common forms of ingestion in the United States.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] As a structural analog of *N*,*N*-dimethyltryptamine (DMT), 5-MeO-DMT is a Schedule 9 prohibited substance under the Poisons Standard.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is not an explicitly nor implicitly controlled substance in Canada as of 2025.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] As of October 2015, 5-MeO-DMT is a controlled substance in China.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] As of 2001 5-MeO-DMT is listed as a controlled substance.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT has been controlled in Turkey since December 2013.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT was made a Schedule I controlled substance in January 2011.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Preliminary clinical findings suggest that 5-MeO-DMT might have antidepressant and anxiolytic effects.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] A 2019 European study with 42 volunteers showed that a single inhalation of 5-MeO-DMT produced sustained enhancement of satisfaction with life, and easing of anxiety, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] A 2018 study found that a single dose of 5-MeO-DMT induced neurogenesis in mice.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] 5-MeO-DMT is being developed and evaluated for potential therapeutic effects in patients with treatment-resistant depression (TRD).
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Biopharmaceutical company GH Research has sponsored a completed phase 1 study in healthy volunteers and phase 1/2 study in TRD patients where 87.5% of patients with TRD were brought into remission on day 7 in the phase 2 part of the study.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] GH Research is currently planning a phase 2b study in TRD patients and have received approval for studies in patients with bipolar II disorder and a current depressive episode and patients with postpartum depression.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In February 2025, GH Research announced that their Phase 2b clinical trial of GH001, met its primary endpoint in patients with TRD.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The trial demonstrated a placebo-adjusted reduction of 15.5 points on the Montgomery-Åsberg Depression Rating Scale (MADRS) at day 8, with 57.7% of patients achieving remission compared to 0% in the placebo group.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] The trial also met all secondary endpoints, and the treatment was well-tolerated with no serious adverse events reported.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] In 2026, the FDA allowed advanced trials for GH001.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Beckley Psytech in collaboration with King's College London evaluated the safety and tolerability of intranasal 5-MeO-DMT in healthy subjects, in a phase 1 study.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] AtaiBeckley's study has completed its Phase 2b stage.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Ultra-short-acting psychedelics like dimethyltryptamine (DMT), bretisilocin and 5-MeO-DMT may be advantageous compared to longer-acting psychedelics like psilocybin in terms of practicality for use as therapeutic interventions in clinical settings.
[src:alkaloid/5-meo-dmt] Concerns have been raised about the potential use of 5-MeO-DMT in medicine due to the extreme and frequently challenging natures of the experiences.
[src:alkaloid/7-methylxanthine] It is shown that systemic treatment with 7-MX appears to be efficient in retarding axial elongation and myopia progression among myopic children.
[src:alkaloid/7-methylxanthine] The treatment is safe and without side effects, and may be continued until 18–20 years of age, when age-related cross-linking of collagen prevents further elongation of the eye.
[src:alkaloid/7-methylxanthine] Additionally, further studies show that oral intake of 7-MX was associated with reduced myopia progression and reduced axial elongation in this sample of myopic children from Denmark.
[src:alkaloid/7-methylxanthine] Randomized controlled trials are needed to determine whether the association is causal.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids are produced by a large variety of organisms including bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] They can be purified from crude extracts of these organisms by acid-base extraction, or solvent extractions followed by silica-gel column chromatography.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Many have found use in traditional or modern medicine, or as starting points for drug discovery.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Other alkaloids possess psychotropic (e.g. psilocin) and stimulant activities (e.g. cocaine, caffeine, nicotine, theobromine), and have been used in entheogenic rituals or as recreational drugs.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids can be toxic (e.g. atropine, tubocurarine).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Although alkaloids act on a diversity of metabolic systems in humans and other animals, they almost uniformly evoke a bitter taste.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The boundary between alkaloids and other nitrogen-containing natural compounds is not clear-cut.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are basic, although some have neutral and even weakly acidic properties.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] In addition to carbon, hydrogen and nitrogen, alkaloids may also contain oxygen or sulfur.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Rarer still, they may contain elements such as phosphorus, chlorine, and bromine.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Compounds like amino acid peptides, proteins, nucleotides, nucleic acid, amines, and antibiotics are usually not called alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Natural compounds containing nitrogen in the exocyclic position (mescaline, serotonin, dopamine, etc.) are usually classified as amines rather than as alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Some authors, however, consider alkaloids a special case of amines.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The name "alkaloids" (German: *Alkaloide*) was introduced in 1819 by German chemist Carl Friedrich Wilhelm Meissner, and is derived from late Latin root *alkali* and the Greek-language suffix -οειδής -('like').
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] However, the term came into wide use only after the publication of a review article, by Oscar Jacobsen in the chemical dictionary of Albert Ladenburg in the 1880s.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The name "alkaloid" was introduced, since at the time, chemists conceptualized the category of "alkaline" in such a way that plants cannot produce alkaline.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] For instance, potash, an alkaline substance that can be extracted from plants by burning, was thought to be either produced during burning, or extracted by plant from the soil.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Subsequent research by chemists to extract the "principle" (what we nowadays call the active ingredient) of medicinal plants, led to the discovery of various substances that had properties resembling alkalines as understood at the time.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] These substances were variously named "salifiable vegetable bases", "vegetable organic compounds", "organic bases", etc.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] After enough such substances were discovered, these substances were classified as "alkaloid", a new chemical category.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] There is no unique method for naming alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Many individual names are formed by adding the suffix "ine" to the species or genus name.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] For example, atropine is isolated from the plant *Atropa belladonna*; strychnine is obtained from the seed of the Strychnine tree (*Strychnos nux-vomica* L.).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Where several alkaloids are extracted from one plant their names are often distinguished by variations in the suffix: "idine", "anine", "aline", "inine" etc.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] There are also at least 86 alkaloids whose names contain the root "vin" because they are extracted from *vinca* plants such as *Vinca rosea* (*Catharanthus roseus*); these are called *vinca* alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloid-containing plants have been used by humans since ancient times for therapeutic and recreational purposes.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] For example, medicinal plants have been known in Mesopotamia from about 2000 BC.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The *Odyssey* of Homer referred to a gift given to Helen by the Egyptian queen, a drug bringing oblivion.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] It is believed that the gift was an opium-containing drug.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] A Chinese book on houseplants written in 1st–3rd centuries BC mentioned a medical use of ephedra and opium poppies.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Also, coca leaves have been used by Indigenous South Americans since ancient times.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Extracts from plants containing toxic alkaloids, such as aconitine and tubocurarine, were used since antiquity for poisoning arrows.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Studies of alkaloids began in the 19th century.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] In 1804, the German chemist Friedrich Sertürner isolated from opium a "soporific principle" (Latin: *principium somniferum*), which he called "morphium", referring to Morpheus, the Greek god of dreams; in German and some other Central-European languages, this is still the name of the drug.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The term "morphine", used in English and French, was given by the French physicist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] A significant contribution to the chemistry of alkaloids in the early years of its development was made by the French researchers Pierre Joseph Pelletier and Joseph Bienaimé Caventou, who discovered quinine (1820) and strychnine (1818).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Several other alkaloids were discovered around that time, including xanthine (1817), atropine (1819), caffeine (1820), coniine (1827), nicotine (1828), colchicine (1833), sparteine (1851), and cocaine (1860).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The development of the chemistry of alkaloids was accelerated by the emergence of spectroscopic and chromatographic methods in the 20th century, so that by 2008 more than 12,000 alkaloids had been identified.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The first complete synthesis of an alkaloid was achieved in 1886 by the German chemist Albert Ladenburg.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] He produced coniine by reacting 2-methylpyridine with acetaldehyde and reducing the resulting 2-propenyl pyridine with sodium.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Compared with most other classes of natural compounds, alkaloids are characterized by a great structural diversity.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Initially, when knowledge of chemical structures was lacking, botanical classification of the source plants was relied on.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] This classification is now considered obsolete.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] More recent classifications are based on similarity of the carbon skeleton (*e.g.*, indole-, isoquinoline-, and pyridine-like) or biochemical precursor (ornithine, lysine, tyrosine, tryptophan, etc.).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] However, they require compromises in borderline cases; for example, nicotine contains a pyridine fragment from nicotinamide and a pyrrolidine part from ornithine and therefore can be assigned to both classes.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] "Protoalkaloids", which contain nitrogen (but not the nitrogen heterocycle) and also originate from amino acids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Examples include mescaline, adrenaline and ephedrine.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Polyamine alkaloids – derivatives of putrescine, spermidine, and spermine.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Pseudoalkaloids – alkaloid-like compounds that do not originate from amino acids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] This group includes terpene-like and steroid-like alkaloids, as well as purine-like alkaloids such as caffeine, theobromine, theacrine and theophylline.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Some authors classify ephedrine and cathinone as pseudoalkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Those originate from the amino acid phenylalanine, but acquire their nitrogen atom not from the amino acid but through transamination.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Some alkaloids do not have the carbon skeleton characteristic of their group.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] So, galanthamine and homoaporphines do not contain isoquinoline fragment, but are, in general, attributed to isoquinoline alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most alkaloids contain oxygen in their molecular structure; those compounds are usually colorless crystals at ambient conditions.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Oxygen-free alkaloids, such as nicotine or coniine, are typically volatile, colorless, oily liquids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Some alkaloids are colored, like berberine (yellow) and sanguinarine (orange).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are weak bases, but some, such as theobromine and theophylline, are amphoteric.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Many alkaloids dissolve poorly in water but readily dissolve in organic solvents, such as diethyl ether, chloroform or 1,2-dichloroethane.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Caffeine, cocaine, codeine and nicotine are slightly soluble in water (with a solubility of ≥1g/L), whereas others, including morphine and yohimbine are very slightly water-soluble (0.1–1 g/L).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids and acids form salts of various strengths.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] These salts are usually freely soluble in water and ethanol and poorly soluble in most organic solvents.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Exceptions include scopolamine hydrobromide, which is soluble in organic solvents, and the water-soluble quinine sulfate.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most alkaloids have a bitter taste or are poisonous when ingested.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloid production in plants appeared to have evolved in response to feeding by herbivorous animals; however, some animals have evolved the ability to detoxify alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Some alkaloids can produce developmental defects in the offspring of animals that consume but cannot detoxify the alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] One example is the alkaloid cyclopamine, produced in the leaves of corn lily.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] During the 1950s, up to 25% of lambs born by sheep that had grazed on corn lily had serious facial deformations.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] These ranged from deformed jaws to cyclopia.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] After decades of research, in the 1980s, the compound responsible for these deformities was identified as the alkaloid 11-deoxyjervine, later renamed to cyclopamine.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids are generated by various living organisms, especially by higher plants – about 10 to 25% of those contain alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Therefore, in the past the term "alkaloid" was associated with plants.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The alkaloids content in plants is usually within a few percent and is inhomogeneous over the plant tissues.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Depending on the type of plants, the maximum concentration is observed in the leaves (for example, black henbane), fruits or seeds (Strychnine tree), root (*Rauvolfia serpentina*) or bark (cinchona).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Furthermore, different tissues of the same plants may contain different alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Beside plants, alkaloids are found in certain types of fungus, such as psilocybin in the fruiting bodies of the genus *Psilocybe*, and in animals, such as bufotenin in the skin of some toads and a number of insects, markedly ants.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Many marine organisms also contain alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Some amines, such as adrenaline and serotonin, which play an important role in higher animals, are similar to alkaloids in their structure and biosynthesis and are sometimes called alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Because of the structural diversity of alkaloids, there is no single method of their extraction from natural raw materials.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most methods exploit the property of most alkaloids to be soluble in organic solvents but not in water, and the opposite tendency of their salts.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Their mixture is extracted first and then individual alkaloids are separated.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Plants are thoroughly ground before extraction.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are present in the raw plants in the form of salts of organic acids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The extracted alkaloids may remain salts or change into bases.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Base extraction is achieved by processing the raw material with alkaline solutions and extracting the alkaloid bases with organic solvents, such as 1,2-dichloroethane, chloroform, diethyl ether or benzene.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Then, the impurities are dissolved by weak acids; this converts alkaloid bases into salts that are washed away with water.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] If necessary, an aqueous solution of alkaloid salts is again made alkaline and treated with an organic solvent.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The process is repeated until the desired purity is achieved.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] In the acidic extraction, the raw plant material is processed by a weak acidic solution (*e.g.*, acetic acid in water, ethanol, or methanol).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] A base is then added to convert alkaloids to basic forms that are extracted with organic solvent (if the extraction was performed with alcohol, it is removed first, and the remainder is dissolved in water).
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The solution is purified as described above.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids are separated from their mixture using their different solubility in certain solvents and different reactivity with certain reagents or by distillation.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] A number of alkaloids are identified from insects, among which the fire ant venom alkaloids known as solenopsins have received greater attention from researchers.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] These insect alkaloids can be efficiently extracted by solvent immersion of live fire ants or by centrifugation of live ants followed by silica-gel chromatography purification.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Tracking and dosing the extracted solenopsin ant alkaloids has been described as possible based on their absorbance peak around 232 nanometers.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Biological precursors of most alkaloids are amino acids, such as ornithine, lysine, phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan, histidine, aspartic acid, and anthranilic acid.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Nicotinic acid can be synthesized from tryptophan or aspartic acid.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Ways of alkaloid biosynthesis are too numerous and cannot be easily classified.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] However, there are a few typical reactions involved in the biosynthesis of various classes of alkaloids, including synthesis of Schiff bases and Mannich reaction.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Schiff bases can be obtained by reacting amines with ketones or aldehydes.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] These reactions are a common method of producing C=N bonds.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] An integral component of the Mannich reaction, in addition to an amine and a carbonyl compound, is a carbanion, which plays the role of the nucleophile in the nucleophilic addition to the ion formed by the reaction of the amine and the carbonyl.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] In addition to the described above monomeric alkaloids, there are also dimeric, and even trimeric and tetrameric alkaloids formed upon condensation of two, three, and four monomeric alkaloids.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] There are also dimeric alkaloids formed from two distinct monomers, such as the *vinca* alkaloids vinblastine and vincristine, which are formed from the coupling of catharanthine and vindoline.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] The newer semi-synthetic chemotherapeutic agent vinorelbine is used in the treatment of non-small-cell lung cancer.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] It is another derivative dimer of vindoline and catharanthine and is synthesised from anhydrovinblastine, starting either from leurosine or the monomers themselves.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids are among the most important and best-known secondary metabolites, i.e. biogenic substances not directly involved in the normal growth, development, or reproduction of the organism.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Instead, they generally mediate ecological interactions, which may produce a selective advantage for the organism by increasing its survivability or fecundity.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] In some cases their function, if any, remains unclear.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] An early hypothesis, that alkaloids are the final products of nitrogen metabolism in plants, as urea and uric acid are in mammals, was refuted by the finding that their concentration fluctuates rather than steadily increasing.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Most of the known functions of alkaloids are related to protection.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] For example, aporphine alkaloid liriodenine produced by the tulip tree protects it from parasitic mushrooms.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] In addition, the presence of alkaloids in the plant prevents insects and chordate animals from eating it.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] However, some animals are adapted to alkaloids and even use them in their own metabolism.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Such alkaloid-related substances as serotonin, dopamine and histamine are important neurotransmitters in animals.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Alkaloids are also known to regulate plant growth.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] One example of an organism that uses alkaloids for protection is the *Utetheisa ornatrix*, more commonly known as the ornate moth.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Pyrrolizidine alkaloids render these larvae and adult moths unpalatable to many of their natural enemies like coccinelid beetles, green lacewings, insectivorous hemiptera and insectivorous bats.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Another example of alkaloids being utilized occurs in the poison hemlock moth (*Agonopterix alstroemeriana).* This moth feeds on its highly toxic and alkaloid-rich host plant poison hemlock (*Conium maculatum*) during its larval stage.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] *A. alstroemeriana* may benefit twofold from the toxicity of the naturally occurring alkaloids, both through the unpalatability of the species to predators and through the ability of *A. alstroemeriana* to recognize *Conium maculatum* as the correct location for oviposition.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] A fire ant venom alkaloid known as solenopsin has been demonstrated to protect queens of invasive fire ants during the foundation of new nests, thus playing a central role in the spread of this pest ant species around the world.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Medical use of alkaloid-containing plants has a long history, and, thus, when the first alkaloids were isolated in the 19th century, they immediately found application in clinical practice.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Many synthetic and semisynthetic drugs are structural modifications of the alkaloids, which were designed to enhance or change the primary effect of the drug and reduce unwanted side-effects.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] For example, naloxone, an opioid receptor antagonist, is a derivative of thebaine that is present in opium.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Prior to the development of a wide range of relatively low-toxic synthetic pesticides, some alkaloids, such as salts of nicotine and anabasine, were used as insecticides.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Their use was limited by their high toxicity to humans.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Preparations of plants and fungi containing alkaloids and their extracts, and later pure alkaloids, have long been used as psychoactive substances.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Cocaine, caffeine, and cathinone are stimulants of the central nervous system.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Mescaline and many indole alkaloids (such as psilocybin, dimethyltryptamine and ibogaine) have hallucinogenic effect.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Morphine and codeine are strong narcotic pain killers.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] There are alkaloids that do not have strong psychoactive effect themselves, but are precursors for semi-synthetic psychoactive drugs.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] For example, ephedrine and pseudoephedrine are used to produce methcathinone and methamphetamine.
[src:alkaloid/alkaloid] Thebaine is used in the synthesis of many painkillers such as oxycodone.
